title.value: Decoding natural sounds in early 'visual' cortex of congenitally blind individuals

license_info.value: Creative Commons CC0 - No Rights Reserved

description.value:
Complex natural sounds, such as bird singing, people talking or traffic noise, induce decodable fMRI activation patterns in early visual cortex of sighted blindfolded participants. That is, early visual cortex receives non-visual and potentially predictive information from audition. However, it is unclear whether the transfer of auditory information to early visual areas is an epiphenomenon of visual imagery or, alternatively, whether it is driven by mechanisms independent from visual experience. 
Here we show that we can decode natural sounds from activity patterns in early “visual” areas of congenitally blind individuals who lack visual imagery. Thus, visual imagery is not a prerequisite of auditory feedback to early visual cortex. Furthermore, the spatial pattern of sound decoding accuracy in early visual cortex was remarkably similar in blind and sighted individuals, with an increasing decoding accuracy gradient from foveal to peripheral regions. This suggests that the typical organisation by eccentricity of early visual cortex develops for auditory feedback even in the lifelong absence of vision. The same feedback to early visual cortex might support visual perception in the sighted and drive the recruitment of this area for non-visual functions in blind individuals.

publications.value:
Vetter, P., Bola, L., Reich, L., Bennett, M., Muckli, L., & Amedi, A. (Accepted/In press). Decoding natural sounds in early “visual” cortex of congenitally blind individuals. Current Biology .

title.value: Brain-wide quantitative data on parvalbumin positive neurons in the rat

citation.value: Bjerke, I. E., Yates, S. C., Puchades, M., Bjaalie, J. G., & Leergaard, T. B. (2020). Brain-wide quantitative data on parvalbumin positive neurons in the rat [Data set]. EBRAINS. [DOI: 10.25493/KR92-C33] [DOI: 10.25493/KR92-C33]: https://doi.org/10.25493%2FKR92-C33

description.value:
This dataset contains quantitative data extracted from four sets of parvalbumin stained sections covering the whole brain of normal, adult Sprague-Dawley rats. Section images from the dataset “Distribution of parvalbumin-positive interneurons in the normal adult rat brain” [1] were analysed using the QUINT workflow. The dataset includes numbers and densities of cells for brain regions defined according to the Waxholm Space atlas of the rat brain and point coordinate data representing labelled cells across the brain. A detailed description of the number and distribution on parvalbumin neurons in hippocampal regions is given in the related publication. To facilitate re-use of the data, the dataset furthermore includes atlas maps and segmented images in .png format and .nut files used to run the analyses.

References:
1. Laja, A., Bjerke, I., Leergaard, T. & Witter, M. Distribution of parvalbumin-positive interneurons in the normal adult rat brain. EBRAINS (2020) https://doi.org/10.25493/8KCQ-3C7.

description.value:
This dataset contains the densities (in fmol/mg protein) of receptors for classical neurotransmitters in Area Te2 using quantitative in vitro autoradiography. The receptor density measurements are provided as density fingerprints (fp; average across samples; mean density and standard deviation for each of the analyzed receptors). 
Also provided are exemplary laminar density profiles (pr; exemplary data from one sample; average course of the density from the pial surface to the border between layer VI and the white matter for each receptor), and/or color-coded autoradiography images (ar; exemplary data from one sample; laminar density distribution patterns for each receptor labeling). Which example profiles and autoradiographs are provided can be found in the given metadata (<< area >>_receptor-metadata.json).
For Area Te2, receptor density measurements were conducted for the following **receptors** by labeling the given binding site (…) with the stated agent […]:

**AMPA** (glutamate) [[³H]AMPA]

**kainate** (glutamate) [[³H]kainate]

**NMDA** (glutamate) [[³H]MK-801]

**mGluR2/3** (glutamate) [[³H] LY 341 495]

**GABA<sub>A</sub>** (GABA) [[³H]muscimol]

**GABA<sub>B</sub>** (GABA) [[³H] CGP54626]

**GABA<sub>A</sub>** (BZ) [[³H]flumazenil]

**muscarinic M₁** (acetylcholine) [[³H]pirenzepine]

**muscarinic M₂** (acetylcholine) [[³H]oxotremorine-M]

**muscarinic M₃** (acetylcholine) [[³H]4-DAMP]

**nicotinic α₄β₂** (acetylcholine) [[³H]epibatidine]

**α₁** (noradrenalin) [[³H]prazosin]

**α₂** (noradrenalin) [[³H]UK-14,304]

**5-HT₁<sub>A</sub>** (serotonin) [[³H]8-OH-DPAT]

**5-HT₂** (serotonin) [[³H]ketanserin]

**D₁** (dopamine) [[³H]SCH23390]

Which sample was used for which receptor density measurement is stated in the given metadata (<< area >>_receptor-metadata.json) accompanying the main data repository. The given metadata also include complementary information about samples and corresponding subjects as well as the analyzed receptors (<< area >>_subjects.csv; << area >>_receptor-info.xlsx).

Zilles, K. et al. (2002). Quantitative analysis of cyto- and receptorarchitecture of the human brain, pp. 573-602. In: Brain Mapping: The Methods, 2nd edition (A.W. Toga and J.C. Mazziotta, eds.). San Diego, Academic Press.

title.value: Atlas of the short fiber bundles inferred from the Human Connectome Project diffusion MRI dataset

description.value: Using the outstanding diffusion MRI dataset of the Human Connectome Project, we inferred the largest atlas to date of reproducible short fiber bundles (less than 8cm) of the human brain. This atlas results from a framework aligning subjects using a diffeomorphic procedure forcing the match of the main cortical sulci. This is a key feature to align correctly the U-bundles, which circumvent the cortical folds. This sulcus-based alignment includes the nonlinear ICBM T1-weighted MRI average in order to drive all the subject’s tractograms (the set of dMRI-based virtual fibers) to the standard ICBM space. Then, a two level clustering (intrasubject and intersubject) is performed on the tractograms to define the most reproducible bundles across subjects. A postregistration with freesurfer space leads to label each bundle according to the nomenclature of the Desikan-Killiany atlas. We deliver probabilistic maps of each bundle in the ICBM space and an aggregated map providing a parcellation of superficial white matter defined from a maximum probability principle.

description.value: In this study we evaluated the effective connectivity between Deep Cerebellar Nuclei (DCN) and cerebral cortex over one hemisphere. To this aim, we performed electrical stimulation of Dentate nucleus simultaneously with wide-field imaging of distributed calcium activity over the contralateral cortical hemisphere. To visualize neuronal activity, we used a transgenic mouse line (Thy1-GCaMP6f) that expresses the fluorescent indicator GCaMP6f in a subset of excitatory neurons.

title.value: Dendritic morphologies of four groups of mouse hippocampal interneurons

citation.value: Bardóczi, Z., Takács, V. T., Major, A., Orosz, Á., Papp, P., Sos, K. E., Mayer, M., Hajós, Z., Szépné Simon, E., Freund, T. F., & Nyiri, G. (2020). Dendritic morphologies of four groups of mouse hippocampal interneurons [Data set]. EBRAINS. [DOI: 10.25493/R156-8CA] [DOI: 10.25493/R156-8CA]: https://doi.org/10.25493%2FR156-8CA

description.value: Computational modelling of hippocampal network mechanisms requires real-life morphological features of the dendritic arbors of interneurons (INs) in the CA1 area. There are several different groups of hippocampal interneurons. We investigated four groups. Hippocampo-septal (HS) INs project both locally and to the medial septum. Oriens-lacunosum-moleculare (OLM) INs are typical local feedback inhibitory neurons. Parvalbumin (PV)- and calretinin (CR)-containing INs represent two different groups of local INs. Here, using viral tracing and immunohistochemistry, we labeled these classes of INs and using scanning electron microscopy (SEM), we measured their dendritic cross-sectional areas and perimeters along the dendritic segments of these neurons. We estimated their volumes with and without mitochondria and estimated their dendritic surface areas as well. We measured and corrected all changes during tissue processing, therefore, all physical parameters represent the real life parameters of these dendrites.

title.value: In vitro binding characterization of [³H] LY2119620 for the muscarinic cholinergic receptor type 2

description.value: Modern modelling and simulation approaches have been exploited to pinpoint and design more potent and specific ligands and allosteric modulators which can be used not only for research, but also for diagnostic and even therapeutic purposes. A crucial component of the ligand development program is the experimental validation of the accuracy and reliability of candidate compounds. We here present the data of the in vitro binding characterization of the novel ligand [<sup>3</sup>H] LY2119620, an allosteric modulator of the cholinergic muscarinic receptor type 2 (M<sub>2</sub>) obtained from the primary motor cortex (M1), the primary somatosensory cortex (S1), the hippocampus (Hip), the striatum (Str), and the cerebellum (Cb) of six adult rat brains. For each brain regions, the dataset comprises (i) the cross-subject average density and standard deviation of the M<sub>2</sub> receptor (in fmol/mg), as determined by labelling with [<sup>3</sup>H] LY2119620, and (ii) the corresponding dissociation constant (K<sub>D</sub>) of this labelling agent (in nM).

title.value: Electrophysiology of thalamocortical projection neurons

citation.value: Clascá, F., & Casas-Torremocha, D. (2020). Electrophysiology of thalamocortical projection neurons [Data set]. EBRAINS. [DOI: 10.25493/DV47-PV3] [DOI: 10.25493/DV47-PV3]: https://doi.org/10.25493%2FDV47-PV3

description.value: This dataset provides a characterization of the electrophysiological intrinsic properties of the thalamocortical neurons as well as the morphology of their somatodendritic compartment. Neurons of this dataset were located in different nuclei, including first-order (i.e. ventral posteromedial, VPM) and higher-order (i. e. posterior, Po) thalamic nuclei. Whole-cell patch-clamp recordings were performed in order to reproduce the input/output relationships and to study the specific properties of the neurons firing rate. The passive properties of the cells were extracted by analyzing current relaxation induced by step voltage changes (IV protocol), while the cellular spontaneous firing and the cellular responses to positive and negative current injections were acquired through gap free and current clamp step protocols, respectively. In some experiments, biocytin was added to the intracellular solution in order to correlate such electrophysiological characterization with the somatodendritic compartment. The accurate data of the electrophysiological intrinsic properties and reconstruction of the somatodendritic compartment of thalamocortical neurons provide in this dataset will be re-usable by any scientist developing biologically based models of local and long-range brain circuitry.

title.value: Metadata Schema of the Common Data Elements for Mental Health (v5)

zip.detail: ###HBP Knowledge Graph Data Platform Citation Requirements
zip.value: download all related data as ZIP

description.value:
Data in the Medical Informatics Platform (MIP) resides in hospital servers and never leaves the hospital. Analyses and experiments are executed with respect to that principle while preserving patients’ anonymity making it infeasible for their identity to be inferred. 
Hospitals importing their data to the Medical Informatics Platform join a federation so as to run analyses on data from other hospital nodes as well. Each federation in the MIP refers to a specific Medical Condition. 
Here the metadata for the federation of hospitals that studies mental health is presented.

This metadata schema, consisting of a total of 191 variables, has the following main variable categories:
**1. Demographic** - 2 variables for basic demographic information that does not reveal patient’s identity
**2. Separation anxiety** - 30 multinomial variables for anxiety concerning several reasons and situations
**3. Fears of specific things or situations** - 23 multinomial variables for fears of several objects, people or
situations
**4. Brain anatomy** - 135 volumetric variables based on a brain atlas. Values have been generated from the brain feature extraction pipeline which uses SPM12

The metadata viewing and management is done by Data Catalogue, a central web portal of MIP. Data Catalogue offers presentation, search and hierarchical visualisation of metadata information for datasets imported into the MIP while providing metadata management features to authorized users. One of its features is parsing metadata descriptions in XLSX files and generating their equivalent in a hierarchical JSON format which the MIP uses. In this repository we upload metadata in both XLSX and the generated JSON format.

title.value: Neocortex-wide fluorescence imaging of neuronal activity during a reach-to-grasp task

citation.value: Quarta, E., Scaglione, A., Lucchesi, J., Sacconi, L., Allegra Mascaro, A. L., & Pavone, F. (2020). Neocortex-wide fluorescence imaging of neuronal activity during a reach-to-grasp task [Data set]. EBRAINS. [DOI: 10.25493/C8P7-6X0] [DOI: 10.25493/C8P7-6X0]: https://doi.org/10.25493%2FC8P7-6X0

description.value: The dataset includes wide-field fluorescence recordings from the dorsal neocortex of both hemispheres of Thy1-GCaMP6f mice (C57BL/6J-Tg(Thy1GCaMP6f)GP5.17Dkim/J; RRID:IMSR_JAX:025393) during a reach-to-grasp task. The GCaMP6f indicator enables visualization of fluctuations in calcium concentration, which is an indirect reporter of neuronal activity, expressed in terms of dF/F0. The behavior of the mouse is recorded via high-speed cameras, synchronized with the fluorescence signal. For selected movements, we provide data about the position of the metacarpus (.csv files), which was extracted from the corresponding .avi file.

title.value: Simultaneous cortical fluorescence imaging and LFP recording in striatum after optogenetic striatal stimulation

citation.value: Montagni, E., Resta, F., Scaglione, A., Spagnolo, B., Pisanello, M., Silieo, L., De Vittorio, M., Pisanello, F., Allegra Mascaro, A. L., & Pavone, F. (2020). Simultaneous cortical fluorescence imaging and LFP recording in striatum after optogenetic striatal stimulation [Data set]. EBRAINS. [DOI: 10.25493/NK4R-2RE] [DOI: 10.25493/NK4R-2RE]: https://doi.org/10.25493%2FNK4R-2RE

description.value: Striatum is involved in cortico-basal ganglia-thalamocortical loop and divided in dorsolateral, dorsomedial and ventral striatum, which are anatomically and functionally distinct. Cortico-striatal connectivity plays a fundamental role in planning movements and cognitive processes. Since striato-cortical communications is largely unexplored, to dissect its connectivity we used a tapered optical fiber implanted unilaterally to optogenetically stimulate targeted domains of striatum in channelrhodopsin(ChR2)-expressing Drd1-Cre awake mice. By changing the light input angle, the illumination is gradually moved along the fiber for striatal region-selective illumination. A microelectrode implanted on the fiber allowed recording of the local field potential from dorsolateral striatum during stimulation. Mice were transfected with AAV9-syn-GCaMP6f for large-scale recording of striatal-evoked neuronal activity using wide-field calcium imaging over right hemisphere. This combination of tools is used to highlight the functional correlation of selected striatal domains with both spatiotemporal cortical patterns over the right cortical mantle, evoked-striatal LFP and evoked-behavior. Preliminary results showed that optogenetic activation of DRD1+-neurons in dorsomedial striatum evoked complex forelimb movements associated with large calcium transients in motor cortex.

description.value: BigBrain is an ultrahigh-resolution three-dimensional (3D) model of a human brain at nearly cellular resolution of 20 micrometers. The model is based on a full 3D reconstruction from digital scans of 7404 histological sections, which were stained for cell bodies. The dataset contains the reconstituted sections in the axial, coronal and sagittal dimension at 20 micrometer resolution, as well as full 3D volumes at different resolutions in the original histological space (matching the 2D sections), as well as the MNI ICBM152 and ADNI spaces.

title.value: Manifold-based Dictionary of the variability of the folding patterns of ten large cortical sulci

description.value:
We are seven billion humans with unique fingerprints but also unique cortical folding patterns and functional architectures. Each sulcus morphological variability can be modeled by a low dimensional manifold, which has been computed from the HCP dataset for five main sulci of the left and right hemispheres: Central sulcus, Precentral gyrus, Superior Temporal Sulcus, Cingulate Sulcus, Lateral Sulcus. 
For each brain of the HCP dataset, the sulci have been automatically identified using the Morphologist toolbox of brainVISA software. Each brain has been affinely normalize to the Talairach standard space. Right sulci have been flipped to be comparable with left sulci. For each sulcus of interest, a pairwise distance matrix has been computed across subject after rigid aligment. Then a 6 dimensional manifold has been computed using Isomap algorithm. For each HCP subject, we deliver the coordinates in these manifolds for further studies assessing the links with behavior or functional organization.

component.value: Electrophysiological, morphological and molecular study of layer 6 neuronal microcircuits in rat primary somatosensory (barrel) cortex

description.value: Electrophysiological characterisation of cortical neurons and synaptically coupled neuronal pairs is essential to understand their functions in brain microcircuits. Electrophysiological data were collected by using single or dual patch-clamp recordings from primary somatosensory (barrel) cortical layer 6 neurons in acute rat brain slices. These data are used for analysing neuronal and synaptic properties and could also be reused for modelling the electrical behaviour of individual neurons and synaptic transmission between them.
